06970nam a22008655i 9783110541397DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2018400616  a97831105413977 a10.1515/97831105413972doi  a(DE-B1597)480675  a(OCoLC)1024050312  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aCD931b.M36 2018 7aPHI0030002bisacsh0481ua020qDE-101222/ger  aND 1450qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/124822:00aManuscripts and Archives :bComparative Views on Record-Keeping /cAlessandro Bausi, Christian Brockmann, Michael Friedrich, Sabine Kienitz. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (XIV, 462 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Manuscript Cultures ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPrologue: Contemporary Practices of Archiving -- tHow to Distinguish between Manuscripts and Archival Records: A Study in Archival Theory -- tArchives from Tibet and the Himalayan Borderlands: Notes on Form and Content -- tThe Ancient World up to Late Antiquity -- tConstitution, Contents, Filing and Use of Private Archives: The Case of Old Assyrian Archives (nineteenth century BCE) -- tArchives in Ancient Egypt, 2500-1000 BCE -- tArchives and Libraries in Greco-Roman Egypt -- tLibraries and Archives in the Former Han Dynasty (206 BCE-9 CE): Arguing for a Distinction -- tSetting a Bishopric / Arranging an Archive: Traces of Archival Activity in the Bishopric of Alexandria and Antioch -- tDocuments, Acts and Archival Habits in Early Christian Church Councils: A Case Study -- tThe Middle Ages -- tWeighing in on Evidence: Documents and Literary Manuscripts in Early Medieval Japan -- tSecuring and Preserving Written Documents in Byzantium -- tArchival Practices in the Muslim World prior to 1500 -- tThe Power of the Pen: Cadis and their Archives -- tIndian Copper-Plate Grants: Inscriptions or Documents? -- tEpilogue: Why and how to compare -- tEpilogue: Archives and Archiving across Cultures-Towards a Matrix of Analysis -- tList of Contributors -- tList of Documents0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aArchives are considered to be collections of administrative, legal, commercial and other records or the actual place where they are located. They have become ubiquitous in the modern world, but emerged not much later than the invention of writing. Following Foucault, who first used the word archive in a metaphorical sense as "the general system of the formation and transformation of statements" in his "Archaeology of Knowledge" (1969), postmodern theorists have tried to exploit the potential of this concept and initiated the "archival turn". In recent years, however, archives have attracted the attention of anthropologists and historians of different denominations regarding them as historical objects and "grounding" them again in real institutions. The papers in this volume explore the complex topic of the archive in a historical, systematic and comparative context and view it in the broader context of manuscript cultures by addressing questions like how, by whom and for which purpose were archival records produced, and if they differ from literary manuscripts regarding materials, formats, and producers (scribes).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aArchivesxHistory. 0aArchivesxMethodology. 0aArchivesxPhilosophy. 0aManuscripts. 4aArchiv. 4aArchäologie des W